Acid on object storage — the four properties, paid for by the log.

Object stores like S-three don't give you transactions natively. Delta lake builds the four acid properties up on top of them.

Atomicity. A transaction commits the moment the next commit file appears in the log. That jay-son write is itself atomic — a single put. Either readers see the new commit, or they don't. Half-written data files written before the commit are simply not part of the table, because no add action references them yet.

Consistency. Every commit is validated against the current table state — schema and constraints — before it's accepted.

Isolation. Delta uses optimistic concurrency control. Two writers prepare their commits independently, and whoever wins the race to write the next commit file wins. The loser re-reads the latest log, checks whether its changes still apply with no conflict on the touched files, and retries.

Durability. The underlying object store handles durability for both the data files and the log files. Once a commit is written, it's persisted.

Why is this exam-relevant? Because the bank's nightly card pipeline and the real-time fraud stream can write to the same table without corrupting each other. Either a commit succeeds and becomes visible, or it conflicts and retries — never a partial result.
